name: Renal: Acid-base
question1: What is an acid, base, pH, and pKa
contents:
Acid is a proton donor


Base is a proton acceptor


pH - is the -log to base 10 of H+ concentration.


Ka - is the dissociation constant - to get equation for pH


  • Ka
  • taking logarithms :
  • log Ka = log [H+] + log [HCO3-] / [H2CO3]
  • subtract log [H+] from both sides
  • log Ka - log [H+] = log [HCO3-] / [H2CO3]
  • next do the same with log Ka in order to move it to the right
  • - log [H+] = - log Ka + log [HCO3-] / [H2CO3]
  • which can be written
  • pH = pKa + log [HCO3-] / [H2CO3]


pKa - the negative logarithm of the dissociation constant. or the pH at which 50% of the drug molecules are ionised and 50% un-ionised.


as H2CO3 is not routinely assayed CO2 may be used in its place. The blood [CO2] is related to the paCO@ by a factor of 0.23 mmol.l-1.kPa-1 or 0,03 mmol.l-1


The generic form of the equation states that for an ACID :

  • pH = pKa + log [ionised form] /[un-ionised form]

The generic form of the equation states that for an BASE :

  • pH = pKa + log [un-ionised form] /[ionised form]
question2: What is a buffer? Write the Hendleson-Hasselbach equation. (Derive)   Buffering in the kidney (3)
contents2:
A buffer is a substance or mixture that minimises the change in pH that would otherwise occur when a stronger acid or base is added.

  • There are three main buffering systems in the kidney:
  • Bicarbonate buffering and reabsorption (main):
  • Hydrogen ions secreted into tubular lumen carbonic acid formed broken down to H2O and CO2 by carbonic anhydrase isoenzyme IV in brush border both reabsorbed into tubular cell converted back to carbonic acid by carbonic anhydrase isoenzyme II bicarbonate and hydrogen ions split
  • Phosphate
  • Ammonia buffer system permits further hydrogen ion secretion:
  • Glutamine produced via metabolism of amino acids in liver ammonia produced in tubular cells by metabolism of glutamine
  • NH3 diffuses into tubular fluid in proximal and distal tubules, or is transported across as NH4+ by Na/H antiporter
  • NH3 combines with H+ in lumen to form NH4+; stays in lumen as tubular cell membrane is poorly permeable to NH4+
  • 50% of secreted NH4+ is reabsorbed in the thick ascending limb of the Loop of Henle - replaces K in the Na/K/2Cl symporter; limited by symporter capacity dissociates to NH3 + H+ in medullary interstitium
  • NH3 then re-enters the collecting duct via diffusion H+ secreted into the collecting duct to produce NH4+ = acid excreted
question3: What is actual Bicarbonate/standard Bicarbonate?  What is Base excess/standard base excess?
contents3:
Actual bicarbonate gives the true plasma bicarbonate concentration 


  • ***(still ionised/un-ionised? as for an acid). pH = pKa + log [ionised form] / [un-ionised form]***
  • As H2CO3 is not routinely assayed CO2 may be used in its place.
  • As (from the derived Hendleson-Hasselbach) which has pH = pKa + log [HCO3-] / [H2CO3]


  • The blood [CO2] is related to PaCO2 by a factor of 0.23 mmol.l-1.kPa-1 or 0.03 mmol.l-1.

Standard bicarbonate REMOVES ANY RESPIRATORY COMPONENT of acidosis/alkalosis; derived from the Siggaard-Andersen nomogram

OR

Bicarb Calculated

  • Actual bicarb = use measured pH and PCO2 in the Henderson Hasselbalch equation
  • Standard bicarb = actual bicarb with sample corrected to pCO2 of 5.3kPa at 37C


BASE EXCESS

  • In 1960 Siggaard-Andersen introduced base excess in blood as an indicator of the non-respiratory component of the acid-base status.
  • Examines the whole metabolic component of any acidosis/alkalosis unlike the standard bicarbonate that only focuses on the bicarbonate.
  • The base excess curve was printed on the Siggaard-Andersen curve nomogram. 
  • The acid-base status in the human organism is described in terms of arterial pH, arterial pCO2 and the extracellular base excess, Base(ecf).
  • Base excess = number of millimoles of strong acid required to titrate 1L of blood to a pH 7.4, at a temperature of 37C with a PCO2 of 5.3 kPa
  • Standard base excess = BE adjusted for blood with Hb = 5g/dl (i.e. anaemic)
  • Haemoglobin is an effective plasma buffer, but any acidotic or alkalotic process affects the whole body, not just the plasma, so the standard base excess is thought to better reflect the amount of acid/alkali required to correct any disturbance in-vivo.
